mporary Grandparenting is the first book to take a sociological approach to grandparenting across diverse country contexts and combines new theorising with up-to-date empirical findings to document the changing nature of grandparenting across global contexts. In this highly original book, leading contributors analyse how grandparenting differs according to the nature of the welfare state and the cultural context, how family breakdown influences grandparenting, and explore men's changing roles as grandfathers. Grandparents today face conflicting norms and expectations about their roles, but act with agency to forge new identities within the context of societal and cultural constraints. Contemporary Grandparenting illuminates key issues relevant to students and researchers from sociology and social policy, including in the fields of family, childhood, ageing and gender studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aGrandparentingxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aArber, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArber, Sara, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaker, Lindsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Lynda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagestad, Gunhild O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerlofson, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuxhold, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKo, Lisanne S.F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahne, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator